Manager's "WHY" Questions

Why validate file contents instead of extensions?

Because extensions can be renamed, while inspecting the actual file contents (magic bytes/MIME) provides stronger assurance of the file type.


---

Why store uploads outside the web root?

To prevent uploaded files from being directly executed by the web server, reducing the risk of Remote Code Execution.


---

Why use a whitelist for file inclusion?

Because it limits file access to known, approved resources and prevents attackers from requesting arbitrary files.


---

Why sanitize HTTP headers?

Because untrusted input in headers can lead to response splitting, cache poisoning, malicious redirects, and other attacks.


---

Interview Summary

Unrestricted File Upload → Uploading malicious files that can lead to Remote Code Execution.

LFI → Reading or including files already on the server.

RFI → Including attacker-controlled remote files, often leading to code execution.

Header Injection → Manipulating HTTP headers to alter browser or server behavior.

Best Defenses → Validate file content, store uploads outside the web root, use whitelists for file inclusion, and sanitize all header values.


These vulnerabilities are common in real-world web applications, and understanding why the defenses work—not just what they are—is exactly the reasoning your manager has been encouraging you to develop.
